Based on the retrieved evidence, DN501 shares the same mechanism of action as darunavir, which is inhibition of HIV-1 protease. Multiple sources confirm that protease inhibitors (PIs) bind to the HIV-1 protease enzyme and block its ability to cleave Gag and Gag-Pol polyproteins, resulting in the production of immature, non-infectious virions. This mechanism is consistent across multiple entries citing darunavir, atazanavir, ritonavir, and other PIs. There is no supporting evidence suggesting DN501 operates through reverse transcription inhibition, viral entry blockade, or T-cell binding interruption. Thus, despite differences in side-effect profiles like hyperglycemia, the fundamental mechanism remains unchanged.
